The strange lack of great dramatists or poets of any - kind in the half century preceding Lucretius and Catullus seems due partly to the ‘ separation in taste and sympathy between the higher classes and the mass of the people ’ (Sellar, p. 265) which made literature the amusement of a narrow circle, and partly to the disturbed political conditions of the time. The continued popularity of the old tragedians may be ascribed to the extent to which they represented some of the best features in the old Roman character (ib. p. 151).
